{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617702"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16487"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16487"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.71,0.1,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65876"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9178"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16487"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51321"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5076"},{"type":"tags","id":"5295"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22007"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65876"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInhaled corticosteroids are the cornerstone of preventive therapy for obstructive respiratory pathologies like asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of inhaled corticosteroids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks leukotriene receptors","Binds nuclear receptors and suppresses inflammatory gene transcription","Inhibits phosphodiesterase enzymes","Stabilises mast cell membranes","Directly relaxes bronchial smooth muscle"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInhaled corticosteroids work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding nuclear receptors and suppressing inflammatory gene transcription\u003C/strong\u003E. They diffuse across cell membranes, bind to cytoplasmic glucocorticoid receptors, and the complex translocates to the nucleus where it regulates gene transcription. This reduces the production of inflammatory mediators in airway cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect relaxation of bronchial smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of beta-2 agonists, not corticosteroids. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECromones like sodium cromoglycate act to \u003Cstrong\u003Estabilise mast cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMontelukast and other leukotriene receptor antagonists exert their therapeutic effect by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eleukotriene receptors\u003C/strong\u003E  \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of phosphodiesterase enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of theophylline. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anti-inflammatory effects occur primarily within the airways, minimising systemic side effects. This local action makes inhaled corticosteroids particularly effective for treating airway inflammation while reducing systemic exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inhaled corticosteroids reduce airway inflammation by suppressing inflammatory gene transcription.","Inhaled corticosteroids bind to glucocorticoid receptors in airway cells and translocate to the nucleus.","The anti-inflammatory effects of inhaled corticosteroids are primarily local, remaining within the airways rather than exerting a systemic effect."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51321"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16487"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51321"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T12:07:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T11:54:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9178"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65876"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying